<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="172">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181660" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole boruca Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boruca" status="new species">Pheidole boruca</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="172">Types Mus. Comp. Zool. Harvard.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="172">etymology Named after the Boruca Amerindians, one of the surviving native tribes of Costa Rica.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="172">
Diagnosis Major: carinulae originating on the frontal lobes curve laterally above the eyes, many reaching the lateral margins of the head seen in full-face view; posterior quarter of dorsal surface of head, including occiput, covered by scattered conspicuous foveae. Media caste present in type series (a possible developmental anomaly). Similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181707" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole violacea Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="violacea">violacea</taxonomicName>
of Costa Rica, especially in the peculiar pattern of cephalic carinulae, but nests on the ground (instead of in arboreal ant gardens), lacks the bluish reflections on the body of the minor, has a media caste, and is different in the major and minor castes in many details of body form, sculpturing, and pilosity as illustrated. See also the less similar 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181715" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole aculifera Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aculifera">aculifera</taxonomicName>
(in the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33735" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole fallax Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fallax">fallax</taxonomicName>
group), 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181689" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole prostrata Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prostrata">prostrata</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181704" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole variegata Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">variegata</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="172">Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 1.10, HL 1.10, SL 0.78, EL 0.20, PW 0.48.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="172">Paratype minor: HW 0.54, HL 0.66, SL 0.84, EL 0.12, PW 0.36.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="172">color Major: body dark, almost blackish brown; appendages medium brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="172">Minor: body blackish brown, appendages medium brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="172">Range Atlantic slope and montane regions of Costa Rica (Longino 1997).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="172">Biology Longino (1997): very common in Winkler samples from mature wet forest, from 50 m elevation at La Selva Biological Station to cloud forest in the Talamancas and at Monteverde. Longino found nests under pieces of dead wood on the ground, and observed workers foraging on the ground day and night.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
